<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">34311440</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2022</Year><Month>02</Month><Day>17</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2022</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>31</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1543-2742</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>31</Volume><Issue>5</Issue><PubDate><Year>2021</Year><Month>Sep</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sport nutrition and exercise metabolism</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sport Nutr Exerc Metab</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Caffeine Mouth Rinse Does Not Improve Time to Exhaustion in Male Trained Cyclists.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>412</StartPage><EndPage>419</EndPage><MedlinePgn>412-419</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/ijsnem.2020-0360</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">ijsnem.2020-0360</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This study investigated the effects of caffeine mouth rinse on cycling time to exhaustion (TTE) and physiological responses in trained cyclists. In a double-blinded randomized counterbalanced cross-over design, 10 recreationally trained male cyclists (mean &#xb1; SD: 32 &#xb1; 3&#xa0;years, 72.8 &#xb1; 5.3&#xa0;kg, 1.78 &#xb1; 0.06&#xa0;m, 13.9% &#xb1; 3.3% body fat, peak power output = 289.4 &#xb1; 24.7&#xa0;W) completed two TTE tests cycling at 75% of peak aerobic power following 24&#xa0;hr of dietary and exercise standardization. Cyclists were administered 25-ml mouth rinses for 5&#xa0;s containing either 85&#xa0;mg of caffeine or control (water) every 5&#xa0;min throughout the exercise tests. No significant improvement in TTE was shown with caffeine mouth rinse compared with control (33:24 &#xb1; 12:47 vs. 28:08 &#xb1; 10:18&#xa0;min; Cohen's dz effect size: 0.51, p = .14). Caffeine mouth rinse had no significant effect on ratings of perceived exertion (p = .31) or heart rate (p = .35) throughout the cycling TTE protocol. These data indicate that a repeated dose of caffeinated mouth rinse for 5&#xa0;s does not improve cycling TTE in recreationally trained male cyclists. However, these findings should be taken with caution due to the small sample size and blinding ineffectiveness, while further well-design studies with larger samples are warranted.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Nabuco</LastName><ForeName>Lara Lima</ForeName><Initials>LL</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Bras&#xed;lia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Saunders</LastName><ForeName>Bryan</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of S&#xe3;o Paulo (USP).</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sousa da Silva</LastName><ForeName>Renato Andr&#xe9;</ForeName><Initials>RA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Bras&#xed;lia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Euro American University Center.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Molina</LastName><ForeName>Guilherme Eckhardt</ForeName><Initials>GE</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Bras&#xed;lia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Reis</LastName><ForeName>Caio Eduardo Gon&#xe7;alves</ForeName><Initials>CEG</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Bras&#xed;lia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2021</Year><Month>07</Month><Day>26</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA